-- China Stocks: BYD, Chongqing Brewery, Sinopec, Poly Real Estate
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2012-02-08T08:22:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-08/china-stocks-byd-chongqing-brewery-sinopec-poly-real-estate.html
Shares of the following companies had
 unusual  moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
as of the close.  The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 55.63 points, or 2.4 percent, to
2,347.53. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  gained 2.9 percent to 2,528.24.  Property stocks:  China Vanke Co.  (000002 CH), the nation’s
biggest listed property developer, rose 2.9 percent to 7.59
yuan. Poly Real Estate Group Co. (600048 CH), the second
largest, added 2.9 percent to 10.42 yuan, even after the second-
biggest developer said yesterday contracted sales dropped 69
percent in January.  Chinese officials will ensure that “loan demand from
first-home families” is met, the People’s Bank of China said on
its website yesterday. A crackdown on real-estate speculation
threatens to trigger a property slump in the world’s second-
biggest economy.  Refiners:  China Petroleum & Chemical Corp. (600028)  (600028 CH), the
nation’s biggest oil refiner, advanced 1.7 percent to 7.78 yuan.
PetroChina Co. (601857 CH), the second largest, climbed 1.7
percent to 10.26 yuan.  Retail gasoline and diesel prices will rise 300 yuan
($47.7) a metric ton from today, the National Development and
Reform Commission, the nation’s top planning agency, said on its
website yesterday.  BYD Co.  (002594 CH), the automaker part-owned by  Warren Buffett ’s Berkshire Hathaway Inc., jumped 7.1 percent to 26.58
yuan, its highest close since Nov. 15. Sales of BYD’s new S6
model may have reached a record 16,000 units last month, beating
the previous record of 15,000 set in December, Jack Yeung, an
analyst at BNP Paribas SA, wrote in a note to clients dated
yesterday.  Chongqing Brewery Co.  (600132 CH), partly owned by
Carlsberg A/S, jumped 5.5 percent to 24.74 yuan, the highest
close since Jan. 11. About 97 percent of shareholders voted to
keep Huang Minggui as chairman, Chongqing Brewery said in a
statement yesterday, ending management uncertainty. The stock
has plunged 66 percent since Dec. 8 following the company’s
announcement that a Hepatitis B vaccine it is developing may be
high-risk and capital-intensive.  --Zhang Shidong. Editor: Chan Tien Hin  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
